    <custom_item>
      type        : REGISTRY_SETTING
      description : "5.10 Ensure 'Microsoft iSCSI Initiator Service (MSiSCSI)' is set to 'Disabled'"
      info        : "Manages Internet SCSI (iSCSI) sessions from this computer to remote target devices.

 The recommended state for this setting is: 'Disabled'.

 Rationale:

 This service is critically necessary in order to directly attach to an iSCSI device.

However, iSCSI itself uses a very weak authentication protocol (CHAP), which means that the passwords for iSCSI communication are easily exposed, unless all of the traffic is isolated and/or encrypted using another technology like IPsec.

This service is generally more appropriate for servers in a controlled environment then on workstations requiring high security."
      solution    : "To establish the recommended configuration via GP, set the following UI path to: 'Disabled'.


 Computer Configuration\Policies\Windows Settings\Security Settings\System Services\Microsoft iSCSI Initiator Service


 Impact:

 The computer will not be able to directly login to or access iSCSI targets."
      reference   : "800-171|3.4.6,800-171|3.4.7,800-53|CM-7,CN-L3|7.1.3.5(c),CN-L3|7.1.3.7(d),CN-L3|8.1.4.4(b),CSF|PR.IP-1,CSF|PR.PT-3,ITSG-33|CM-7,LEVEL|2S,NIAv2|SS13b,NIAv2|SS14a,NIAv2|SS14c,NIAv2|SS15a,SWIFT-CSCv1|2.3"
